<p>How much idea generation to do and how wide you go with it should be dependent on the size and value of the project. If itâ€™s small, itâ€™s probably not worth exploring too deeply, whereas if itâ€™s large then you must be confident youâ€™ve explored every potential opportunity.</p>

<h2 id="activities-you-should-do">Activities you should do</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Create concepts for solutions that solve the problem in different ways in lowest fidelity that can give you sufficient confidence.</li>
  <li>Illustrate the proposed user journey and how the system works.</li>
  <li>Create simple wireframes that explain the core idea.</li>
  <li>Define implications and open questions.</li>
  <li>Evaluate concepts with pros and cons.</li>
  <li>Have a recommendation and rationale why.</li>
  <li>Work with engineers to understand the technical constraints.</li>
  <li>Work with engineers to understand technical implications of your concepts.</li>
  <li>Gather feedback on your concepts from the UX team, your product team and product manager.</li>
  <li>Validate your designs with user testing or customer data.</li>
  <li>Reach agreement with your team about which of the proposed approaches to move forward with.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="activities-you-could-do">Activities you could do</h2>

